=begin pod
=head2 insert-with-values

B<Note: The native version of this routine is deprecated in gtk4-lib() since version 4.10>

Creates a new row at C<$position>. C<$iter> will be changed to point to this new
row. If C<$position> is -1, or larger than the number of rows in the list, then
the new row will be appended to the list. The row will be filled with the
values given to this function.

Calling
B<gtk_list_store_insert_with_values> (list_store, iter, position...)`
has the same effect as calling:

with the difference that the former will only emit L<Gnome::Gtk4::R-TreeModel|/content-docs/api2/reference/Gtk4/R-TreeModel>::row-inserted
once, while the latter will emit L<Gnome::Gtk4::R-TreeModel|/content-docs/api2/reference/Gtk4/R-TreeModel>::row-inserted,
L<Gnome::Gtk4::R-TreeModel|/content-docs/api2/reference/Gtk4/R-TreeModel>::row-changed and, if the list store is sorted,
L<Gnome::Gtk4::R-TreeModel|/content-docs/api2/reference/Gtk4/R-TreeModel>::rows-reordered for every inserted value.

Since emitting the L<Gnome::Gtk4::R-TreeModel|/content-docs/api2/reference/Gtk4/R-TreeModel>::rows-reordered` signal repeatedly can
affect the performance of the program, C<.insert-with-values()>
should generally be preferred when inserting rows in a sorted list store.

